# Web Components live docs — desired properties

## Desired state

Interactive **documentation** for Web Components that shows **editable** markup and a **live preview** stays **isolated** (styles and scripts do not break the host doc site) and **keeps the snippet and the running instance in sync** when that is a project requirement.

## Properties

- **P1 (isolation)**: The preview runs in a **separate** document (for example `iframe` with `srcdoc` or an equivalent) so host CSS/JS and doc-theme scripts do not collide with the component’s runtime.
- **P2 (playground host)**: The **editor/shell** around the preview is a **non-conflicting** stack (commonly a **vanilla** custom element) so the same Lit (or other) version as the documented bundle does not double-load incompatibly in the parent page.
- **P3 (bidirectional sync)**: When the product requires it, **code edits** update the preview, and **attribute-level interactions** in the preview that are represented in the snippet **round-trip** to the editor without feedback loops; JS-only state remains in a controlled init path.
- **P4 (controlled contract)**: If components are “controlled” from outside, the preview bootstrap wires the **event → property** loop so the demo does not appear frozen; reflected attributes in the code pane match the public contract.
- **P5 (debouncing)**: High-frequency code changes are **throttled** so the preview does not thrash.
- **P6 (build integrity)**: Component bundles used in the preview include the **registered** implementation (no silent tree-shaking of custom-element registration).

## Anti-patterns

- Mounting the full component in the **Starlight** page root DOM for real demos of production bundles when isolation is required.
- Relying on **side-effect-only** imports for registration without ensuring the class remains in the built artifact.
- Pasting only non-reflected **props** in the snippet when the user expects a faithful HTML view — document where JS-only setup lives.

